% Chapter: The Cohomological Calculus of Constructions (C⁴)
% Part of the CCTT Monograph — Proof Calculus, Chapter I

\chapter{The Cohomological Calculus of Constructions}
\label{ch:c4-calculus}

The preceding chapters developed CCTT as a \emph{verification framework}:
OTerms, axiom chains, \v{C}ech cohomology, and a proof-term language for
witnessing equivalence.  In this chapter we take a foundational step
further: we define the \textbf{Cohomological Calculus of Constructions}
($\mathrm{C}^4$), a full dependent type theory that unifies the Calculus of
Inductive Constructions (CIC, the kernel of Lean and Coq) with
sheaf-theoretic cohomology and cubical path structure.

The key idea is that $\mathrm{C}^4$ has \emph{all} the expressive power of
CIC---universes, dependent products and sums, inductive types, and
universe polymorphism---but every type is \emph{fibered} over a site
category, and the type theory has native rules for descent, gluing,
and cohomological obstruction.  A proof in $\mathrm{C}^4$ can appeal to any
Mathlib theorem (imported as an axiom), reason about code (via OTerm
embedding), and use cohomological decomposition to reduce global
properties to per-fiber obligations.

\section{Design Principles}

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Strict superset of CIC.}  Every CIC judgment is a valid
  $\mathrm{C}^4$ judgment (with the trivial one-fiber site).  $\mathrm{C}^4$ is
  a conservative extension.

\item \textbf{Cubical paths are native.}  Path types
  $\Path_A\, a\, b$ are defined via the interval $\interval$, not via
  inductive identity types.  Univalence and function extensionality hold
  definitionally.

\item \textbf{Fiber universes.}  Every universe $\mathcal{U}_i$ carries
  a site decoration $\site$; a type $A : \mathcal{U}_i^{\site}$ is a
  sheaf of types over $\site$.

\item \textbf{Descent as a typing rule.}  If you can prove a property
  on every fiber of a cover $\{U_\alpha\}$ with compatible overlaps,
  the descent rule produces a global proof.  This internalizes
  $\Hone = 0 \Rightarrow$ global section.

\item \textbf{Mathlib import is a functor.}  A validated translation
  functor $\Phi : \mathrm{CIC}_{\mathrm{Lean}} \to \mathrm{C}^4$ maps Lean~4
  declarations to $\mathrm{C}^4$ axioms, preserving provability.

\item \textbf{OTerms are first-class.}  The denotational semantics of
  Python programs (OTerms) inhabit a universe $\mathcal{U}_\PyObj$, and
  CCTT axioms (D1--D24, etc.) are equalities in that universe.
\end{enumerate}


\section{Syntax}

\subsection{Sorts and Universes}

$\mathrm{C}^4$ has a cumulative hierarchy of universes:
\[
  \mathsf{Prop} \subset \mathcal{U}_0 \subset \mathcal{U}_1 \subset
  \mathcal{U}_2 \subset \cdots
\]

Each universe carries an optional \textbf{site annotation}
$\mathcal{U}_i^{\site}$, indicating that types in this universe
are sheaves over the site $\site$.  When the site is trivial
(a single object), we recover CIC.  When the site is the
CCTT fiber site (objects = duck-type fibers, morphisms = subtyping),
types decompose along fibers.

\begin{definition}[Site-Decorated Universe]
A \textbf{site-decorated universe} $\mathcal{U}_i^{\site}$ is a universe
whose types are contravariant functors
$A : \site^{\mathrm{op}} \to \mathcal{U}_i$.  That is, for each object
$U \in \site$, $A(U) : \mathcal{U}_i$ is a type, and for each morphism
$f : V \to U$, there is a restriction map
$\restr{}{f} : A(U) \to A(V)$.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Terms}

The term language extends CIC with cubical and cohomological primitives:

\[
\begin{array}{rcll}
  t, A, B & ::= & x & \text{variable} \\
  & \mid & \mathcal{U}_i^{\site} & \text{site-decorated universe} \\
  & \mid & \Pi(x : A).\, B & \text{dependent function} \\
  & \mid & \lambda(x : A).\, t & \text{abstraction} \\
  & \mid & t\; u & \text{application} \\
  & \mid & \Sigma(x : A).\, B & \text{dependent pair} \\
  & \mid & (t, u) \mid \pi_1(t) \mid \pi_2(t) & \text{pair intro/elim} \\
  & \mid & \mathsf{Ind}(\Delta) & \text{inductive type} \\
  & \mid & \mathsf{rec}_\Delta(t, \vec{c}) & \text{recursion principle} \\
  & \mid & \interval & \text{interval type} \\
  & \mid & \mathsf{0}_\interval \mid \mathsf{1}_\interval & \text{interval endpoints} \\
  & \mid & \Path_A\, a\, b & \text{path type} \\
  & \mid & \langle i \rangle\, t & \text{path abstraction} \\
  & \mid & t\; r & \text{path application} \\
  & \mid & \transp^i\, A\, \varphi\, t & \text{transport} \\
  & \mid & \hfilling^i\, A\, [\vec{s}]\, t_0 & \text{homogeneous comp} \\
  & \mid & \mathsf{Glue}[\varphi \mapsto (T, e)]\, A & \text{glue type} \\
  & \mid & \restr{t}{U} & \text{fiber restriction} \\
  & \mid & \mathsf{desc}(\{t_\alpha\}, \{p_{\alpha\beta}\})
    & \text{descent (gluing)} \\
  & \mid & \mathsf{import}_{\mathrm{Lean}}(\mathit{name}) & \text{Mathlib axiom} \\
  & \mid & \den{P} & \text{OTerm embedding} \\
\end{array}
\]

\subsection{Contexts}

A context $\Gamma$ is a list of typed variable declarations, possibly
annotated with fiber restrictions:
\[
  \Gamma ::= \cdot \mid \Gamma, x : A \mid \Gamma, x :_U A
\]
where $x :_U A$ means ``$x$ has type $A$ on fiber $U$.''


\section{Judgments}

$\mathrm{C}^4$ has five judgment forms:

\begin{enumerate}
\item $\Gamma \vdash A : \mathcal{U}_i^{\site}$
  \quad (``$A$ is a type in universe $\mathcal{U}_i$ over site $\site$'')
\item $\Gamma \vdash t : A$
  \quad (``$t$ has type $A$'')
\item $\Gamma \vdash A \equiv B : \mathcal{U}_i^{\site}$
  \quad (``$A$ and $B$ are definitionally equal types'')
\item $\Gamma \vdash t \equiv u : A$
  \quad (``$t$ and $u$ are definitionally equal terms of type $A$'')
\item $\Gamma \vdash_U t : A$
  \quad (``$t$ has type $A$ on fiber $U$'')
\end{enumerate}

The fiber-restricted judgment $\Gamma \vdash_U t : A$ is the key
novelty: it allows reasoning about the behavior of a program on a
specific type fiber without committing to global behavior.


\section{Typing Rules}

\subsection{Standard CIC Rules}

The standard CIC rules carry over unchanged.  We show only the
key ones for reference:

\begin{gather}
\frac{}{\Gamma \vdash \mathcal{U}_i : \mathcal{U}_{i+1}}
\quad (\mathcal{U}\text{-form})
\tag{Univ}
\\[6pt]
\frac{\Gamma \vdash A : \mathcal{U}_i \qquad
      \Gamma, x : A \vdash B : \mathcal{U}_j}
     {\Gamma \vdash \Pi(x:A).\, B : \mathcal{U}_{\max(i,j)}}
\quad (\Pi\text{-form})
\tag{$\Pi$F}
\\[6pt]
\frac{\Gamma, x : A \vdash t : B}
     {\Gamma \vdash \lambda(x:A).\, t : \Pi(x:A).\, B}
\quad (\Pi\text{-intro})
\tag{$\Pi$I}
\\[6pt]
\frac{\Gamma \vdash f : \Pi(x:A).\, B \qquad \Gamma \vdash a : A}
     {\Gamma \vdash f\; a : B[x := a]}
\quad (\Pi\text{-elim})
\tag{$\Pi$E}
\\[6pt]
\frac{\Gamma \vdash A : \mathcal{U}_i \qquad
      \Gamma, x : A \vdash B : \mathcal{U}_j}
     {\Gamma \vdash \Sigma(x:A).\, B : \mathcal{U}_{\max(i,j)}}
\quad (\Sigma\text{-form})
\tag{$\Sigma$F}
\end{gather}

\subsection{Cubical Rules}

The interval and path rules follow Cohen--Coquand--Huber--M\"ortberg:

\begin{gather}
\frac{\Gamma \vdash A : \mathcal{U}_i \qquad
      \Gamma \vdash a : A \qquad \Gamma \vdash b : A}
     {\Gamma \vdash \Path_A\, a\, b : \mathcal{U}_i}
\quad (\Path\text{-form})
\tag{PathF}
\\[6pt]
\frac{\Gamma, i : \interval \vdash t : A \qquad
      t[i := 0] \equiv a \qquad t[i := 1] \equiv b}
     {\Gamma \vdash \langle i \rangle\, t : \Path_A\, a\, b}
\quad (\Path\text{-intro})
\tag{PathI}
\\[6pt]
\frac{\Gamma \vdash p : \Path_A\, a\, b \qquad
      \Gamma \vdash r : \interval}
     {\Gamma \vdash p\; r : A}
\quad (\Path\text{-elim})
\tag{PathE}
\end{gather}

\noindent with the computation rules $(\langle i \rangle\, t)\; r
\equiv t[i := r]$ and the boundary rules
$p\; \mathsf{0} \equiv a$, $p\; \mathsf{1} \equiv b$.

\begin{definition}[Transport]
Given a path in the universe $A : \interval \to \mathcal{U}_i$:
\[
\frac{\Gamma, i : \interval \vdash A : \mathcal{U}_i \qquad
      \Gamma \vdash t : A[\mathsf{0}/i]}
     {\Gamma \vdash \transp^i\, A\, t : A[\mathsf{1}/i]}
\quad (\mathsf{transp})
\]
\end{definition}

\subsection{Fiber Restriction Rules}

These rules are the core novelty of $\mathrm{C}^4$:

\begin{gather}
\frac{\Gamma \vdash t : A \qquad U \in \mathrm{Ob}(\site)}
     {\Gamma \vdash_U \restr{t}{U} : \restr{A}{U}}
\quad (\text{restrict})
\tag{Res}
\\[6pt]
\frac{\Gamma \vdash_U t : A \qquad
      f : V \to U \text{ in } \site}
     {\Gamma \vdash_V \restr{t}{f} : \restr{A}{f}}
\quad (\text{pullback})
\tag{Pull}
\end{gather}

These say: any global term can be restricted to a fiber, and
fiber-local terms can be pulled back along morphisms.

\subsection{The Descent Rule}

The descent rule is the crown jewel of $\mathrm{C}^4$.  It
internalizes the sheaf condition:

\begin{definition}[Descent Rule]
\label{def:descent-rule}
Given a cover $\covers = \{U_\alpha\}_{\alpha \in I}$ of the terminal
object in $\site$, local sections $t_\alpha : \restr{A}{U_\alpha}$ for
each $\alpha$, and compatibility witnesses
$p_{\alpha\beta} : \restr{t_\alpha}{U_\alpha \cap U_\beta} \equiv
\restr{t_\beta}{U_\alpha \cap U_\beta}$ satisfying the cocycle
condition on triple overlaps:
\[
\frac{
  \begin{array}{c}
    \forall \alpha.\; \Gamma \vdash_{U_\alpha} t_\alpha : \restr{A}{U_\alpha}
    \\[4pt]
    \forall \alpha, \beta.\;
    \Gamma \vdash_{U_\alpha \cap U_\beta}
    p_{\alpha\beta} : \restr{t_\alpha}{U_{\alpha\beta}} \equiv
    \restr{t_\beta}{U_{\alpha\beta}}
    \\[4pt]
    \forall \alpha, \beta, \gamma.\;
    \restr{p_{\alpha\gamma}}{U_{\alpha\beta\gamma}} =
    \restr{p_{\beta\gamma}}{U_{\alpha\beta\gamma}} \circ
    \restr{p_{\alpha\beta}}{U_{\alpha\beta\gamma}}
  \end{array}
}
{\Gamma \vdash \mathsf{desc}(\{t_\alpha\}, \{p_{\alpha\beta}\}) : A}
\quad (\text{descent})
\]
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[Descent = $\Hone = 0$]
The descent rule is applicable if and only if the first \v{C}ech
cohomology of the cover $\covers$ with coefficients in
$\underline{\mathrm{Aut}}(A)$ vanishes:
\[
  \Hone(\covers, \underline{\mathrm{Aut}}(A)) = 0
  \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad
  \text{descent data glues to a global section.}
\]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
The forward direction is the classical descent theorem in algebraic
geometry (SGA~1, Expos\'e VIII).  A \v{C}ech 1-cocycle
$\{g_{\alpha\beta}\}$ with values in $\mathrm{Aut}(A)$ is a collection
of transition functions on double overlaps satisfying the cocycle
condition.  The cohomology class $[g] \in \Hone$ is the obstruction
to finding a global section.  If $\Hone = 0$, every cocycle is a
coboundary: there exist $h_\alpha \in \mathrm{Aut}(\restr{A}{U_\alpha})$
such that $g_{\alpha\beta} = h_\beta^{-1} \circ h_\alpha$ on
$U_\alpha \cap U_\beta$.  Then $h_\alpha(t_\alpha)$ glue to a
global section.

The reverse direction: if a global section $t$ exists, set
$t_\alpha = \restr{t}{U_\alpha}$ and $p_{\alpha\beta} = \mathsf{refl}$.
The cocycle is trivial ($g_{\alpha\beta} = \mathrm{id}$), hence a
coboundary, so $[\mathrm{id}] = 0 \in \Hone$.
\end{proof}


\section{Computation Rules}

\subsection{$\beta$-reduction (Standard)}
$(\lambda(x:A).\, t)\; u \equiv t[x := u]$.

\subsection{Restriction Computation}
Restriction distributes over constructors:
\begin{align}
  \restr{(\lambda x.\, t)}{U} &\equiv \lambda x.\, \restr{t}{U}
  \tag{$\lambda$-res} \\
  \restr{(t, u)}{U} &\equiv (\restr{t}{U}, \restr{u}{U})
  \tag{$\Sigma$-res} \\
  \restr{(\langle i \rangle\, t)}{U} &\equiv
  \langle i \rangle\, \restr{t}{U}
  \tag{Path-res}
\end{align}

\subsection{Descent Computation}
The descent term computes on restriction:
\[
  \restr{\mathsf{desc}(\{t_\alpha\}, \{p_{\alpha\beta}\})}{U_\alpha}
  \equiv t_\alpha
  \tag{desc-$\beta$}
\]

This is the key computation rule: descending and then restricting
gives back the local section.  Combined with the restriction computation
rules, this ensures that the descent operation is computationally
well-behaved.

\subsection{Axiom Computation}
OTerm axioms compute as rewrite rules:
\[
  \den{\ell\sigma} \equiv \den{r\sigma}
  \quad \text{when } (\ell \equiv r) \in \mathcal{A}_{\mathrm{CCTT}}
  \text{ and } \sigma \text{ is a valid substitution}
  \tag{axiom-$\beta$}
\]


\section{Inductive Types}

$\mathrm{C}^4$ supports general inductive types via the same schema as CIC:

\begin{definition}[Inductive Type]
An inductive type declaration $\mathsf{Ind}(\Delta)$ specifies:
\begin{enumerate}
\item A type former $D : \vec{\alpha} \to \mathcal{U}_i$
\item Constructors $c_j : \vec{\beta_j} \to D(\vec{a_j})$
  with the strict positivity condition
\item A recursion principle $\mathsf{rec}_D$
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

In addition, $\mathrm{C}^4$ supports \textbf{higher inductive types}
(HITs) with path constructors, as in cubical Agda.  The PyComp HIT
from Chapter~\ref{ch:hits} is an instance:

\begin{example}[PyComp as a HIT in $\mathrm{C}^4$]
\begin{align*}
  \mathsf{data}\; \PyObj &: \mathcal{U}_0 \;\mathsf{where} \\
  \mathsf{OVar}   &: \mathsf{String} \to \PyObj \\
  \mathsf{OLit}   &: \mathsf{Value} \to \PyObj \\
  \mathsf{OOp}    &: \mathsf{OpName} \times \mathsf{List}(\PyObj) \to \PyObj \\
  \mathsf{OFold}  &: \mathsf{OpName} \times \PyObj \times \PyObj \to \PyObj \\
  \mathsf{OCase}  &: \PyObj \times \PyObj \times \PyObj \to \PyObj \\
  \mathsf{OFix}   &: \mathsf{String} \times \PyObj \to \PyObj \\
  &\vdots \\
  \mathsf{D1}     &: \Path_\PyObj\,
    (\mathsf{OOp}(+, [a, b]))\,
    (\mathsf{OOp}(+, [b, a]))
    \quad \text{(commutativity path)} \\
  \mathsf{D2}     &: \Path_\PyObj\,
    (\mathsf{OOp}(+, [a, \mathsf{OOp}(+, [b, c])]))\,
    (\mathsf{OOp}(+, [\mathsf{OOp}(+, [a, b]), c]))
    \\
  &\vdots
\end{align*}

The 24 dichotomy paths D1--D24 are path constructors of the HIT,
meaning they hold definitionally in $\mathrm{C}^4$.  Any equation that
can be derived from these paths via path composition is automatically
provable.
\end{example}


\section{The OTerm Universe}

\begin{definition}[OTerm Universe]
The \textbf{OTerm universe} $\mathcal{U}_\PyObj$ is a universe in
$\mathrm{C}^4$ whose types are OTerms.  It is equipped with:
\begin{enumerate}
\item An \textbf{embedding} $\den{\cdot} : \mathsf{Python} \to
  \mathcal{U}_\PyObj$ that compiles Python ASTs to OTerms.
\item A \textbf{site structure} where objects are duck-type fibers
  (e.g., $\mathsf{TInt}$, $\mathsf{TStr}$, $\mathsf{TList}$) and
  morphisms are subtyping relations.
\item \textbf{Axiom equalities}: for each CCTT axiom $\ell \equiv r$,
  a path $\Path_{\mathcal{U}_\PyObj}\, \den{\ell}\, \den{r}$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[Completeness of OTerm Axioms]
The CCTT axiom set $\{D_1, \ldots, D_{24}\} \cup \{P_1, \ldots, P_{48}\}$
is complete for the equational theory of $\PyObj$ in the following sense:
if $\den{f} = \den{g}$ in the denotational semantics, then there exists
a path in $\mathcal{U}_\PyObj$ from $\den{f}$ to $\den{g}$ constructible
from the axiom paths and the HIT structure.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
By the universal property of the HIT: $\PyObj$ is the free algebra
modulo the path constructors.  If $\den{f} = \den{g}$ in the
denotational model, then the quotient map identifies them, so a
path exists in the HIT.

In practice, the path search algorithm (Chapter~\ref{ch:path-search})
finds this path as a sequence of axiom applications
$D_{i_1}(\sigma_1) \cdot D_{i_2}(\sigma_2) \cdots D_{i_k}(\sigma_k)$.
\end{proof}


\section{Relationship to CIC}

\begin{theorem}[Conservative Extension]
\label{thm:conservative-extension}
$\mathrm{C}^4$ is a conservative extension of CIC: if $\Gamma \vdash_\mathrm{CIC} t : A$,
then $\Gamma \vdash_{\mathrm{C}^4} t : A$, and conversely, if $\mathrm{C}^4$ derives
$\Gamma \vdash t : A$ where $\Gamma$, $t$, and $A$ are in the CIC fragment
(no fiber restrictions, no descent, no OTerms), then $\Gamma \vdash_\mathrm{CIC} t : A$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
The forward direction is immediate: CIC rules are a subset of
$\mathrm{C}^4$ rules (take the trivial site with one object).

For the reverse direction, we show that the additional $\mathrm{C}^4$
rules---fiber restriction, descent, OTerm embedding---cannot derive new
CIC judgments.  This follows because:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Fiber restriction on the trivial site is the identity.
\item Descent on the trivial site (single cover element) reduces to
  the assumption rule.
\item OTerm embedding introduces new constants but no new equalities
  between CIC terms.
\end{enumerate}
A more careful proof proceeds by showing that the
$\mathrm{C}^4$ $\to$ CIC translation (erasing fiber annotations and
descent to identity) preserves typing derivations.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}
Conservativity means: any Lean theorem can be used in $\mathrm{C}^4$
without worrying about soundness.  The import functor
$\Phi : \mathrm{CIC}_\mathrm{Lean} \to \mathrm{C}^4$ preserves all
proof-relevant content.  We develop this functor in
Chapter~\ref{ch:mathlib-integration}.
\end{remark}


\section{Why $\mathrm{C}^4$ Goes Beyond Lean and F*}

\subsection{Native Fiber Decomposition}

In Lean, to prove that a function is correct ``on all integer inputs
separately from all string inputs,'' one must manually set up a
case analysis.  In $\mathrm{C}^4$, the fiber restriction rule
automatically decomposes the proof obligation along the type fibers
of the site.  A proof of the form
\[
  \forall \tau \in \{\mathsf{TInt}, \mathsf{TStr}, \mathsf{TList}\}.\;
  \Gamma \vdash_\tau P(\tau)
\]
immediately yields $\Gamma \vdash P$ (global) via descent, provided the
overlap conditions are satisfied.

\subsection{Cohomological Obstruction Reporting}

When a proof attempt \emph{fails}, $\mathrm{C}^4$ doesn't just say
``proof failed.''  It computes the $\Hone$ class and reports the
\emph{specific obstruction}: which fiber overlaps are inconsistent
and why.  This is qualitatively richer than the ``tactic failed''
error messages in Lean or Coq.

\subsection{OTerm Computation}

In Lean, proving properties of Python programs requires first
formalizing Python's semantics in Lean~4---a massive overhead.
In $\mathrm{C}^4$, the OTerm universe provides a direct,
compositional semantics for Python.  CCTT axioms give computation
rules.  A proof that ``\texttt{sum(range(n))} equals
$n(n-1)/2$'' is a short path in $\mathcal{U}_\PyObj$:
\[
  \den{\mathsf{sum}(\mathsf{range}(n))}
  \xrightarrow{P_{12}}
  \mathsf{OFold}(+, 0, \mathsf{range}(n))
  \xrightarrow{D_{18}}
  \mathsf{OOp}(\div, [\mathsf{OOp}(\times, [n, n-1]), 2])
\]

In Lean, this would require importing a library for Python semantics,
stating the equivalence as a lemma, and writing a tactic proof---likely
10--50$\times$ more effort.

\subsection{Combined Code-and-Math Reasoning}

The deepest advantage: $\mathrm{C}^4$ lets you mix code reasoning
(OTerms + axioms) with pure mathematics (Mathlib imports) in a single
proof.  For example, proving that a numerical algorithm converges can
combine:
\begin{itemize}
\item A Mathlib theorem about the convergence of the underlying
  mathematical sequence.
\item An OTerm axiom chain showing that the code implements the
  mathematical recurrence.
\item A fiber decomposition showing that integer overflow doesn't
  affect the result for inputs in range.
\end{itemize}

No other system provides this seamless integration.
